00:15:05,846 --> 00:15:14,034
So he says that, well, he's talking now specifically about monks going into the wilderness, to the root of a tree, to an empty space and all that.

117
00:15:15,035 --> 00:15:20,261
But basically, folding his legs crosswise and setting his body straight.

118
00:15:20,798 --> 00:15:23,581
So we needn't take that too literally.

119
00:15:23,621 --> 00:15:26,225
You can sit, you can do with your legs what you want.

120
00:15:26,267 --> 00:15:27,408
You can take them off if you want.

121
00:15:28,269 --> 00:15:37,443
It's basically keeping the body straight, keeping the body energized, lifting it, and establishing mindfulness in front of him.

122
00:15:37,484 --> 00:15:41,269
In other words, bringing mindfulness to bear.

123
00:15:42,191 --> 00:15:45,777
So he breathes in mindful and he breathes out mindful.

124
00:15:46,279 --> 00:15:51,405
And then it says that while breathing in long, he knows I am breathing in long.

125
00:15:52,306 --> 00:15:59,014
And when breathing out, he knows I am breathing out long and then breathing short and then breathing out short.

126
00:15:59,293 --> 00:16:00,514
So this is your beginning.

127
00:16:00,554 --> 00:16:11,427
This is contacting the breath as you feel it, whenever you sit down, whenever you start your practice, unless there's something immediate that draws your attention.

128
00:16:11,879 --> 00:16:25,133
I mean, if you sit down, if you just had a big upset, for instance, and you sit down and you have to deal with this upsetting feeling, you know, somebody's let you down or made you angry or whatever, then of course you would go immediately to that.

129
00:16:25,212 --> 00:16:26,374
You wouldn't go to the breath.

130
00:16:27,554 --> 00:16:32,440
But normally speaking, you would begin with the breath.

131
00:16:32,780 --> 00:16:36,083
And of course, what he's saying is just get in contact with it.

132
00:16:36,544 --> 00:16:38,966
Know that it's long, know that it's short.

133
00:16:39,807 --> 00:16:46,240
Now...

134
00:16:47,062 --> 00:16:49,404
And then experiencing the whole body.

135
00:16:49,485 --> 00:16:51,947
I will breathe in experiencing the whole body.

136
00:16:51,988 --> 00:16:52,508
I'll breathe out.

137
00:16:52,828 --> 00:17:00,196
So, uh, having contacted the breath and got the feeling of it, one then begins to stay with the full length of the body.

138
00:17:00,235 --> 00:17:02,337
The body of the breath is the body here.

139
00:17:02,378 --> 00:17:03,339
Isn't the body.

140
00:17:03,779 --> 00:17:07,864
It's the body of the breath, the beginning, the middle section and the end.

141
00:17:08,344 --> 00:17:12,488
Now, when you do that, you're not looking for a middle point of your breath.

142
00:17:13,009 --> 00:17:17,053
You're beginning at the, the beginning is, is the moment it begins.

143
00:17:17,354 --> 00:17:23,640
The whole business of coming to the end of the in-breath is the middle, and the end is the end.

144
00:17:24,520 --> 00:17:31,747
So it's a middle and end, and it's the beginning, middle, and end of the out-breath.

145
00:17:35,611 --> 00:17:39,894
And he says, calming the body process, I will breathe in and breathe out, you see.

146
00:17:40,296 --> 00:17:42,678
Now, it's not as though you do that purposefully.

147
00:17:43,038 --> 00:17:45,099
As soon as you put your attention on the breath,

148
00:17:45,551 --> 00:17:51,759
You will feel this calmness come and you keep doing it until the calmness becomes established.

149
00:17:52,740 --> 00:17:55,202
It's not something that you force upon yourself.

150
00:17:56,265 --> 00:18:03,773
So the example, he says, is of a clever turner or turner's apprentice.

151
00:18:04,314 --> 00:18:10,040
This is on a machine that carves wood, a bowl or something.

152
00:18:10,982 --> 00:18:13,404
I am making a long turn.

153
00:18:13,565 --> 00:18:16,867
And while making a short turn, he knows I'm making a short turn.

154
00:18:17,689 --> 00:18:21,491
And so monks, a monk while breathing knows I'm breathing long.

155
00:18:21,731 --> 00:18:27,436
And while breathing out, he knows I'm breathing out long.

156
00:18:28,137 --> 00:18:31,701
He knows I'm breathing in short and breathing out short.

157
00:18:31,980 --> 00:18:36,263
Experiencing the whole body, he trains himself this way.

158
00:18:37,766 --> 00:18:39,467
Experiencing the whole body, I breathe out.

159
00:18:39,507 --> 00:18:40,567
That's the whole body of the breath.

160
00:18:40,970 --> 00:18:43,792
Calming the bodily process, I breathe in.

161
00:18:44,213 --> 00:18:47,857
Calming the bodily process, I breathe out.

162
00:18:48,298 --> 00:18:48,578
Okay?

163
00:18:49,240 --> 00:19:09,103
So there you've got three points there where you first of all contact the breath, then you settle into the breath, and very slowly the breath begins to create just the fact of making a neutral, quiet sensation the object of your meditation.

164
00:19:09,403 --> 00:19:14,751
has the effect of silencing the mind, calming the heart and stilling the body.

165
00:19:17,596 --> 00:19:22,523
Now, you have to be careful not to take this too literally.

166
00:19:22,624 --> 00:19:30,737
In no tradition does it say that I've worked with, does it say that you're supposed to be saying I am breathing out.

167
00:19:31,290 --> 00:19:35,315
One of the problems of Pali is it doesn't have a passive voice.

168
00:19:35,776 --> 00:19:41,181
So you can't say the breath is being breathed, right?

169
00:19:42,261 --> 00:19:48,208
In English, we can say they drove the car.

170
00:19:48,949 --> 00:19:52,172
And then we can turn it around and say the car was driven by them.

171
00:19:52,231 --> 00:19:53,493
Well, you can't say that in Pali.

172
00:19:53,933 --> 00:19:55,895
So you've only got an active sense.

173
00:19:56,957 --> 00:19:58,699
And the commentaries point out that

174
00:19:59,101 --> 00:20:04,167
A dog or a jackal knows where they're going and they know where they're sitting down.

175
00:20:05,009 --> 00:20:06,290
But obviously they don't say it.

176
00:20:07,211 --> 00:20:12,378
So it's just really a recognition.

177
00:20:12,778 --> 00:20:16,064
Now, the word that is used is paginati.

178
00:20:16,744 --> 00:20:22,491
So it's not a case of just knowing that the breath is rising or falling.

179
00:20:22,873 --> 00:20:24,535
It's knowing in a particular way.

180
00:20:24,885 --> 00:20:30,510
So remember this word paginati, the noun is panya, wisdom, insight.

181
00:20:30,810 --> 00:20:34,375
So it's looking at it from the three characteristics of existence.

182
00:20:36,297 --> 00:20:43,603
The relationship we have with things, wanting, not wanting, impermanence, mainly it's impermanence with the breath.

183
00:20:44,304 --> 00:20:46,185
And of course, the body is breathing.

184
00:20:46,266 --> 00:20:46,905
It's not me.

185
00:20:47,606 --> 00:20:50,028
When you're watching the body, the body is just breathing.

186
00:20:50,410 --> 00:20:52,951
So there's your anatta, it's not me, yeah?

187
00:20:55,497 --> 00:21:00,104
OK, so that brings us to the breath, which time is moving on.

